# Day 14 - Find All Anagrams in a String

## Problem Statement
Given two strings `s` and `p`, return an array containing all the starting indices of `p`'s anagrams in `s`. The answer can be returned in any order.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findAnagrams(string s, string p) {
        int left = 0;
        vector<int> ans;
        vector<int> freq(128, 0);
        int missing = p.size();

        for (char c : p) {
            freq[c]++;
        }

        for (int right = 0; right < s.size(); right++) {
            if (freq[s[right]] > 0) {
                missing--;
            }

            freq[s[right]]--;

            if (right - left + 1 > p.size()) {
                if (freq[s[left]] >= 0) {
                    missing++;
                }

                freq[s[left]]++;
                left++;
            }

            if (right - left + 1 == p.size() && missing == 0) {
                ans.push_back(left);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};




## Time Complexity
**O(n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses the **Sliding Window** technique along with a frequency array. Initially, the frequency of each character in string `p` is stored, and a variable `missing` keeps track of how many characters are still required to form an anagram. As the window expands over `s`, the frequency of the current character is updated, and `missing` is decreased whenever a required character is found. If the window size exceeds the length of `p`, the leftmost character is removed from the window, restoring its frequency and updating `missing` if necessary. Whenever the window size equals the length of `p` and `missing` becomes zero, the starting index of the current window is added to the answer since it represents an anagram of `p`.
